1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. e3 {QUESTION: Is 5...c5 a good move
here?} (5. a3 {is the subject of Chapter Seven. White commits the sin in this
game of simply playing 'moves' rather than playing with a purpose. This allows
the future World Champion Max Euwe time to build up an attack.}) 5... d5 $1 {
Even back nearly 100 years ago, Euwe knew the attacking set-up with ...d5 and ...Bd6 that I am recommending.} ({ANSWER: Black's ...c5 is a typical pawn thrust
to challenge the centre, but here it is not so good.} 5... c5 6. d5 $1 {
is the sort of position Black is trying to avoid. The b7-bishop is out of the
game, and White is going to build up a central space advantage with e3-e4,
Bf1-d3 and so on.}) 6. cxd5 ({After} 6. Bd3 {Black can proceed with:} Bd6 (6...
dxc4 {can transpose to a favourable Queen's Gambit Accepted set-up, for example}
7. Bxc4 a6 8. O-O b5 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. a3 c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 {which was already
very comfortable for Black in D.Cori Tello-G.Sargissian, Villafranca 2010}) 7.
O-O O-O 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Bb2 a6 {, see Chapter Nine for more details.}) 6... exd5
7. Bd3 Bd6 {This is a much more active square for the bishop than e7.} 8. O-O
O-O 9. Qc2 Re8 (9... a6 {prevents 10 Nb5 but allows the central break} 10. e4
dxe4 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nd7 14. Bg5 Qe8 {which is roughly
equal.}) 10. Bd2 {This bishop performs no useful role here.} (10. b3 {and
Bc1-b2 was better.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Rae1 Ne4 12. Bc1 Ndf6 (12... a6 {
preventing Nc3-b5 and then getting on with the kingside plan was preferable.})
13. Nb5 Bb4 14. Rd1 c6 15. Nc3 Bd6 {Resuming normal operations.} 16. h3 Bc7 17.
Ne2 Rc8 18. b3 Bb8 19. Bb2 {EXERCISE: What should Black do next? --- ANSWER:
There are many possible moves, but I like Euwe's strategy here} c5 $1 {A pawn
break to release the pieces, namely the c8-rook and the b7-bishop.} 20. dxc5
Rxc5 {Euwe plays for an isolated queen's pawn (IQP) as he senses he has
greater piece play and the chance to attack.} (20... bxc5 {controlling d4 and
giving rise to hanging pawns, was certainly an option.}) 21. Qb1 Qc7 22. b4 {
This looks good, but is met by a clever riposte,} (22. Ned4 {was more solid.})
22... Ng5 $1 23. Nf4 ({Others:} 23. bxc5 Nxf3+ 24. gxf3 Qh2# {was the main
tactical idea behind 22...Ng5.}) (23. Ned4 Rc4 $1 24. Bxc4 dxc4 25. Rfe1 Nxf3+
26. Nxf3 Bxf3 27. gxf3 Qh2+ 28. Kf1 Nh5 {and now the threat is ...Nf4 and ...Qh1 mate. Some great attacking ideas there.}) 23... Nxf3+ 24. gxf3 Rc6 25. Bb5
{It looks as though Black has just blundered, but Euwe had seen further.} Nh5
$1 26. Qf5 (26. Bxc6 Nxf4 27. exf4 Qxf4 {with mate very soon.}) 26... Nxf4 27.
Qxf4 Rg6+ 28. Kh1 d4 $1 {This is a natural yet very strong move, which blows
open the long diagonal leading to White's king on h1. It is fitting that the
Queen's Indian bishop on b7 delivers the denouement.} 29. Bc1 ({Or} 29. Qxc7
Bxf3+ 30. Kh2 Bxc7# {.}) 29... Bxf3+ $1 {. Mate will follow soon.} 0-1

