prevent Nc3-b5 ideas with} Bxc3 17. bxc3 Rd8 {looks OK for Black.})) 8. Bf4 d6
9. Qe3+ (9. Nc3 Bg7 10. e4 {would transpose to 7...d6 above.}) 9... Be7 10. Nc3
O-O 11. Qd2 Re8 12. g3 Bf8 13. Bg2 {EXERCISE: What should Black do here: a) 13.
..b5, b) 13...Ne4 or c) 13...Nbd7 - ? --- ANSWER: They are all playable, but
Black does best to try and seize the initiative with:} Ne4 {In these Benoni
type pawn structures, it is often a good idea to get in ...Ne4 and exchange
knights if possible.} ({The alternatives are:} 13... b5 {, trying to get the
queenside play going; for example,} 14. b4 Nbd7 15. O-O Rc8 16. Rac1 Nb6 {
does not look to bad either.}) (13... Nbd7 14. O-O {, and now ...Ne4 or even ...c4 and ...Nc5 plans to invade the b3-square (or maybe the d3-square) are
